**Problem**

A gpio is used as an interrupt to wakeup after a deep sleep. After some sleep/wakeup cycle, the processor hangs (it can hangs after less than ten, or a lot more, no identified "rules").

```c++
#include "mbed.h"

DigitalOut led(LED1);
InterruptIn btn(PC_13);
 
void callback(void) {
    led = 1 - led;
}

int main() {
    btn.rise(&callback);
    while(1) {
        sleep();
    }
}
```

Initially, I've try the exact same code with a LowPowerTicker instead of the InteruptIn. It gives the exact same behavior.

I would like to implement a callback mechanism (to my class) similar to `serial.attach()` where you assign your own function when na IRQ is generated. Is it possible that the class will send me a not only IRQ but some result too? ie:

`test.h`
```cpp
#include "mbed.h"

class Test {
  public:
    Test();
    void something();
    int get();
    void attach(Callback<void()> function);

  private:
    Callback<void()> _mycb;
    int _number;
};
```

`test.cpp`
```cpp
